1
00:00:07,692 --> 00:00:36,923
Namotasa bhagavato arahato sama sambodasa Namotasa bhagavato arahato sama sambodasa Namotasa bhagavato arahato sama sambodasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:38,235 --> 00:00:40,539
So I've chosen to look at compassion.

3
00:00:40,560 --> 00:00:52,902
So this is the last of our four Brahma Viharas, the dwelling place of the gods, of the highest gods, by which we mean these are the most beautiful mental states that we can achieve.

4
00:00:52,942 --> 00:00:56,268
So we've done love, done joy, done equanimity.

5
00:00:56,387 --> 00:00:58,612
So compassion is the last one.

6
00:00:59,493 --> 00:01:03,399
So I'd like to start with my own little story here.

7
00:01:03,750 --> 00:01:18,739
I went along the hippie trail around about the 70s and I ended up in Calcutta during the Indo-Pakistan war when Bangladesh became its own, you know, got its liberation from West Pakistan.

8
00:01:19,462 --> 00:01:32,254
And every day for three weeks when we were expecting bombers to come over, I used to go to this Sikh restaurant and on the opposite side of the road, there was a woman with a huge goita, you know, under her chin.

9
00:01:32,275 --> 00:01:33,599
I passed that woman every day.

10
00:01:33,879 --> 00:01:34,921
I never gave her a penny.

11
00:01:36,893 --> 00:01:45,754
One day I came back and just as I turned around the corner, there was a little girl there who must have been well over seven, undernourished, looked very young.

12
00:01:46,977 --> 00:01:53,873
And she was squatted down chewing a dried out black banana skin.

13
00:01:55,102 --> 00:02:01,147
And she had this sort of self-possession, really, to cover her sex, because all she had was this little dress.

14
00:02:01,888 --> 00:02:03,370
And I walked straight past her, you see.

15
00:02:03,950 --> 00:02:13,318
So I've got these two images from this callow youth, and they're very difficult for me to remember them without a certain sense of pain.

16
00:02:13,679 --> 00:02:21,205
And, of course, the reason the pain is there, not simply because of seeing this sort of suffering, which I just had never seen before.

17
00:02:21,225 --> 00:02:22,948
I mean, there were...

18
00:02:24,969 --> 00:02:28,876
There were sick people everywhere, lepers, people with elephantitis.

19
00:02:28,955 --> 00:02:30,679
I mean, they were there on the pavement.

20
00:02:31,680 --> 00:02:34,745
And of course, what pains is that I didn't respond.

21
00:02:34,764 --> 00:02:36,768
I didn't put a penny in that woman's hand.

22
00:02:36,888 --> 00:02:40,334
She sat there all day, completely emotionless with her hand out like that.

23
00:02:41,155 --> 00:02:45,882
And I didn't go out and buy a banana for this little girl, you see.

24
00:02:46,569 --> 00:02:55,290
So here we have what happens to us, what you feel is that you haven't responded.

25
00:02:55,330 --> 00:02:59,921
You haven't responded from a compassionate heart for whatever reason.

26
00:03:00,913 --> 00:03:05,778
So it all begins with that connection, which we call empathy and sometimes sympathy.

27
00:03:05,799 --> 00:03:08,562
I just want to make a little distinction there.

28
00:03:08,741 --> 00:03:14,687
When we say, I mean, this is just arbitrary distinction because these words are used in different ways.

29
00:03:15,468 --> 00:03:28,322
Sympathy these days has some suggestion of pity, you know, but sympathy for me or to make this distinction is when you have to imagine in a way what the person is suffering.

30
00:03:28,301 --> 00:03:44,302
so i've never been i've never been starving i've been i've been hungry but then i've always had food i've never been in a state where i'm actually starving you know and so all i can do is is imagine what it must be like because i felt hungry so there's a sort of connection there

31
00:03:44,924 --> 00:03:48,492
But when it comes to, say, refugees, I've never been a refugee.

32
00:03:48,513 --> 00:03:58,899
I haven't a clue what it means to suddenly up and out your home, to find yourself on the road without much money, having to buy your way, sometimes being attacked.

33
00:03:58,960 --> 00:03:59,540
Who knows?

34
00:04:01,022 --> 00:04:12,322
So there's a point where there's a sympathy where you have to imagine what the person is going and there's empathy where you've actually had an experience which connects you.

35
00:04:12,842 --> 00:04:21,697
So that's just a little distinction I want to make so that we're clear when we're sympathizing and we're actually empathizing because I think sometimes we think we're empathizing

36
00:04:21,677 --> 00:04:30,250
when actually we're imagining, which isn't, if it all leads to the same place, which is a compassionate act, a compassionate word, I mean, there's not really a problem.

37
00:04:30,290 --> 00:04:35,057
But I thought I'd hang on to that little definition just for clarity's sake.

38
00:04:35,918 --> 00:04:41,266
So then the Buddha himself uses a word anukampa.

39
00:04:42,148 --> 00:04:49,338
And the word anu, the prefix anu, is a suggestion of movement towards, movement.

40
00:04:49,319 --> 00:05:05,269
and the kampa actually means trembling so he says whatever a teacher can do for his students out of the anu kampa out of this this connection with his with his students i have done for you

41
00:05:06,447 --> 00:05:13,242
So this anukampa is that point where you have that sense in your own heart of the suffering of the other.

42
00:05:13,302 --> 00:05:24,927
It's that connection, whether it's imaginative sympathy or whether it's empathic connection.

43
00:05:26,038 --> 00:05:30,004
The other word we use is karuna, which actually has its root in doing.

44
00:05:31,045 --> 00:05:47,867
The word in the Sanskrit, kra, I think it's ka, means doing, but it was also used for holy, it was part of the rituals of the Vedas.

45
00:05:47,887 --> 00:05:51,793
So you get this word karuna, which is actually the action.

46
00:05:51,773 --> 00:06:21,324
um you might call it the sacrifice or the sacrament okay so um the the when we when we have responded to somebody's suffering no matter what it is you know the smallest to that to the most uh awful uh that's a mosquito by the way that i'm walking away uh there are two modes one is passive and one is active so in the passive mode

47
00:06:21,862 --> 00:06:28,367
it's often good enough just to be with the person, you know, not even to say anything.

48
00:06:28,827 --> 00:06:38,355
I mean, an obvious case would be when the person is either extremely ill and is just there in bed and all you can do is actually accompany them.

49
00:06:38,737 --> 00:06:40,577
And of course, when somebody is dying.

50
00:06:41,819 --> 00:06:47,423
But I think what we come across when we have that sort of situation is our sense of powerlessness.

51
00:06:48,024 --> 00:06:51,867
And that's very difficult for us because we want to do something, you know, you want to do something.

52
00:06:51,848 --> 00:07:00,269
But, you know, if we are sensitive enough to the situation and to the person, I mean, you don't have to ask them, for heaven's sake.

53
00:07:01,552 --> 00:07:05,824
Often it's good enough just to be with them, you know, just to accompany them.

54
00:07:06,714 --> 00:07:20,795
And when it comes to compassionate action, when you're actually going to do something, then our tendency, I think, is to try and overdo, you know, and to slip into the error of the do-gooder.

55
00:07:20,814 --> 00:07:28,786
I mean, we've all got it in us, which is when we want to do the good we want to do for your benefit, whether you want it or not.

56
00:07:29,788 --> 00:07:32,252
So, of course, this really gets up people's noses.

57
00:07:32,471 --> 00:07:32,992
So...

58
00:07:34,322 --> 00:07:36,206
It was a good idea to ask them what they want to do.

59
00:07:36,927 --> 00:07:51,353
Even if what your suggestion is rejected and even if you know that your suggestion would actually be the better thing to do, even so we've got to pull back a bit and let the person who's suffering have the last say.

60
00:07:53,071 --> 00:08:06,127
But often when we do over-help like that, perhaps it's coming from some sort of inner feeling of wanting to be esteemed, to be loved, all the usual rubbish that we suffer from, you see.

61
00:08:12,233 --> 00:08:18,201
So now, it's often easier to say what...

62
00:08:18,298 --> 00:08:22,745
a virtue is by saying what it isn't.

63
00:08:23,326 --> 00:08:25,290
So we know it's not do-gooding.

64
00:08:26,531 --> 00:08:34,143
So these are reactions that we have when we come across suffering.

65
00:08:36,586 --> 00:08:43,496
The first one would be in a sort of extreme case where the person is really suffering.

66
00:08:43,476 --> 00:08:48,629
And there you've got to have that sort of sense of courage to be with them.

67
00:08:48,668 --> 00:08:55,102
It's very difficult if the person is really in a lot of pain, especially when they're dying.

68
00:08:56,024 --> 00:09:03,020
I read a book about this poor woman who was screaming, screaming every time she died.

69
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:21,009
you know towards the end of her life and eventually the doctor decided to sedate her you know with the obviously the permission of of the family so it often takes a bit of courage to to be with somebody who's in real pain or suffering

70
00:09:20,990 --> 00:09:39,797
There are certain situations which might be a work situation, but it can be somebody you're looking after where you have reactions of disgust, where they're sick, where they're suffering from diarrhea, all the impurities of the body manifest.

71
00:09:41,038 --> 00:09:48,229
And somehow you have to recognize the disgust and yet still come from the heart of compassion.

72
00:09:49,457 --> 00:10:15,616
we can often be caught unawares you know like somebody has found somebody's asked us to do something and we sort of feel messed up you know i had my day carefully planned and now they want me to do this and want me to do that especially within a family and you can get you can feel yourself being angry about that so again it's it's being aware of these negative emotions that come up these negative mental states and and still focusing on what you can do for the person

73
00:10:17,437 --> 00:10:27,669
Sometimes a person hurts themselves, an accident for instance, and you might be wanting to blame them.

74
00:10:27,950 --> 00:10:29,491
So stupid, how could you do that?

75
00:10:30,173 --> 00:10:39,764
I remember I once had an assistant here who put the ladder up against the gutter on the decking.

76
00:10:39,745 --> 00:10:44,114
And the ladder slipped and he just fell flat onto his face almost.

77
00:10:44,335 --> 00:10:46,820
Luckily, there was nothing but a bit of a bruise.

78
00:10:47,400 --> 00:10:51,509
But I could hear myself saying, well, that was stupid, wasn't it?

79
00:10:52,687 --> 00:11:20,703
i didn't say it no i didn't say no no no i i then went up and and uh made sure that he was okay uh but you've got to be careful you can of course if it's somebody close to you feel quite overcome by grief and that can have a sort of an immobilizing effect you know and again it's just resting with that and trying to sort of uh come above it come above it and and to to connect with the person

80
00:11:20,683 --> 00:11:26,875
And that way I think we can keep these emotional states at bay, you might say.

81
00:11:26,975 --> 00:11:34,169
You might have to deal with them afterwards, but not while you're in some sort of situation with them, you know.

82
00:11:34,770 --> 00:11:42,826
I mean, you can understand things like panic, you know, when, say, a child hurts itself and the parents just panic, you know.

83
00:11:42,807 --> 00:12:00,158
Well obviously that doesn't help, doesn't help the child, but it's again hopefully bringing that mindfulness, that connection with our own hearts and that reaction and then to rise above it and respond.

84
00:12:01,724 --> 00:12:03,988
There's pity.

85
00:12:04,128 --> 00:12:06,072
That's another one which isn't particularly nice.

86
00:12:06,493 --> 00:12:14,827
And that's coming from a superior position, often because we're trying to guard ourselves against actually connecting with what's happening.

87
00:12:14,847 --> 00:12:16,130
You know, it's all poor thing.

88
00:12:16,171 --> 00:12:17,653
You know, I feel so sorry for you.

89
00:12:17,714 --> 00:12:19,496
You know, I know how you feel.

90
00:12:21,586 --> 00:12:31,520
So often we find that that's because we're a bit afraid of facing our own possible sickness and eventual death.

91
00:12:31,561 --> 00:12:45,802
There can be a sense of relief, like when somebody has a serious illness, as we have in our family, and you can first of all feel the fear.

92
00:12:45,822 --> 00:12:47,745
Well, if it's in the family, I might get it.

93
00:12:48,586 --> 00:12:51,269
And then a sense of relief, well, it's not me, is it?

94
00:12:52,671 --> 00:12:59,158
So we have to understand that as just basically coming from this false view of self, etc.

95
00:12:59,700 --> 00:13:03,063
And not to sort of get all guilty about that.

96
00:13:03,225 --> 00:13:06,729
It's just a reaction.

97
00:13:07,129 --> 00:13:10,594
But again, it's this ability to rise above it.

98
00:13:12,278 --> 00:13:17,004
These I've picked up from various things that I've read.

99
00:13:17,104 --> 00:13:19,586
There's what's known as empathy bias.

100
00:13:20,167 --> 00:13:36,447
So if a nurse, for instance, is in a ward, but she has a or he has a rather particular connection with one of the patients, then you might find the nurse visiting them slightly more often.

101
00:13:36,427 --> 00:13:43,668
and not really heeding what somebody is calling from the other side of the ward because they don't particularly like them.

102
00:13:44,009 --> 00:13:46,014
So there's always that going on.

103
00:13:47,345 --> 00:13:48,826
Codependency.

104
00:13:48,947 --> 00:14:00,323
So that's a bit of a problem because if a person is getting a lot of self-esteem from helping, it's very difficult for them not to stop.

105
00:14:00,803 --> 00:14:08,154
And so often they're feeding the person who's actually suffering so that they don't have to stop doing good.

106
00:14:08,302 --> 00:14:20,143
I knew a mother, you see, who had, her son was a drug addict and she was always helping him, you know, like paying for his rent when he didn't have it and buying food for him, you know.

107
00:14:20,583 --> 00:14:24,990
And I said to her, I said, well, what you're doing is just feeding his habit financially.

108
00:14:25,030 --> 00:14:27,375
She says, yes, she says, but I'm his mother.

109
00:14:27,355 --> 00:14:38,715
so no she couldn't get over that sort of feeling of um guilt if she stopped helping her son but it would have been the best thing to do that

110
00:14:40,736 --> 00:14:47,909
I think you have to be careful when you are dealing with a long situation of somebody whom you're looking after, perhaps.

111
00:14:48,812 --> 00:14:56,306
And that's, of course, your emotional boundary to know when you're being taken advantage of, even perhaps abused.

112
00:14:59,331 --> 00:15:02,576
So that's something else to be careful about.

113
00:15:03,721 --> 00:15:16,346
and sometimes we find ourselves becoming very involved in a compassionate charity

114
00:15:16,715 --> 00:15:32,263
I'm just thinking of people who get very much involved with refugees, on the side completely of the refugees, and they can have a lack of recognising what it's doing to them.

115
00:15:32,363 --> 00:15:40,376
So you get that sort of burnout and then a resentment from it, what they call compassion fatigue.

116
00:15:40,727 --> 00:15:47,297
And I think that's easy to fall into just as, because, you know, there's so much bad news.

117
00:15:47,977 --> 00:16:09,586
Everywhere you go, there's just bad news, you know, and, and you can, you can feel your heart going out to various situations and various people, but in this, but in the end, you've got to recognize that, well, enough's enough, you know, stop feeding, stop feeding all the bad news and try and find some good news.

118
00:16:13,802 --> 00:16:40,283
Sometimes overemphasizing that sort of helping people and becoming too attached to somebody might blind us to the fact that we might be, in a sense, not allowing them to reflect upon their own situation and take moral stance about themselves.

119
00:16:40,263 --> 00:16:48,770
um i'm just thinking of an adhd you know this um uh what's what have i got here just a minute um

120
00:16:50,860 --> 00:17:15,196
yeah that sort of hyperactive impulsive behavior and somebody you know might for instance just get into gambling because of it and and we're being we're being over compassionate we're not actually it's the problem with medicalizing something is that the person then drops their moral responsibility towards themselves you know oh well i'm

121
00:17:15,515 --> 00:17:34,923
I'm ADHD you know or I'm on on the whatever it is so it's a case of also recognizing that we might be making excuses for them we might be therefore avoiding difficult conversations you know

122
00:17:35,630 --> 00:17:39,454
So all these things are sort of things to be wary of.

123
00:17:40,135 --> 00:17:43,140
And it's not as though we have to go around with a great big list.

124
00:17:43,980 --> 00:17:47,546
Every time we help somebody, you've got to have your list out just in case you're doing something wrong.

125
00:17:48,968 --> 00:18:03,207
It's more in the sense of recognizing that when we are being compassionate, there's probably some undertone that's going on there, coming from this wrong sense of ego, this wrong sense of self.

126
00:18:03,186 --> 00:18:12,099
but there is of course great virtues to be had from compassion and one of them is patience of course which we've dealt with you know

127
00:18:12,873 --> 00:18:19,861
One of the telltales, I think, of compassion is that you're actually deeply happy about it.

128
00:18:19,881 --> 00:18:23,826
This is not the happiness of joy or the happiness of buying an ice cream.

129
00:18:24,346 --> 00:18:32,155
This is that sense of an inner worthiness, an inner sense that you're doing the right thing.

130
00:18:32,175 --> 00:18:40,145
It's a deeper sense of joy, which I think you've all experienced at some point or other when we've helped people.

131
00:18:40,125 --> 00:19:09,795
so that's the sign of of compassion we're not supposed to be suffering when you're being compassionate you're not supposed to be suffering i mean that would be ridiculous and in fact this confusion came up when i was in a particular meditation center where they had eventually it was a lay people have been discussed they eventually came to the conclusion that the buddha could not have been compassionate because it had been suffering how ridiculous that is is it so we have to be careful there um

132
00:19:11,327 --> 00:19:32,509
there's uh i'll just mention it because it's a whole subject on its own but the the tibetan practice of tonglen is all about making that connection with others you know um payment children has a very good meditation up on youtube an introduction shall we say so i

